\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Backwards Flanks
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Flankings ! Backwards
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes, the band with have to perform a 
\noun on
Backwards Flank
\noun default
, where performers must change direction from or to a backwards march.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, when marching field left, parallel to the sideline, traversed
 home (traversing explained in Subsection
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "subsec:Traversing"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), a backwards flank to the left would put the performer's body facing the
 sideline, marching backwards (back field).
 It is a backwards flank because the march direction after the flank was
 backwards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The other type example is starting with a backwards march.
 For example, when marching backwards perpendicular to the sideline, a backwards
 flank to the right would put the performer's direction of travel field
 right in a forwards march.
 It is a backwards flank because the march direction before the flank was
 backwards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is not common for a backwards march backwards to flank into a backwards
 march, but can be seen (for example in Subsection
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "subsec:Ian's-I"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To backwards flank, simply place the left foot in the new direction of travel
 on the downbeat of the flank.
 There is no spinning on the heels and balls like there is in a normal flank.
\end_layout

