\begin_layout Standard

\noun on
Traversing
\noun default
 is marching one direction while the upper body faces a different direction,
 up to 90° left or right.
 It is common to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

traverse home
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to allow the band to march one direction and point the instruments towards
 the home sideline for best sound quality.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
When the horns are not facing the audience, the sound travels in a different
 direction and an effective high-cut is applied.
 This is sometimes taken advantage of in shows, but most of the time the
 horns are traversed home to maximize high-end.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Traversing involves rotating the upper body so that it is facing one direction
 while marching in another.
 Therefore, it is important to traverse correctly to reduce the amount of
 strain and tension caused on the spine.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Traversing involves two directions: the 
\noun on
March Direction
\noun default
, and the 
\noun on
Facing Direction
\noun default
.
 The march direction is the direction the performer is marching.
 This could be forwards, backwards, or any angle in between.
 The facing direction is the direction the upper body is facing while marching.
 It is possible for the facing direction to be anywhere within the range
 of –90° to +90° from the direction of the marching direction.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To march oblique angles, inverse the march direction (Hip Switch, explained
 in Subsection
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "subsec:Hip-Switch"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "traversing-never-backwards-at-90"

\end_inset

It should be noted that performers will never march backwards when the facing
 angle is 90° of the marching angle (they will forwards march instead).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A rare exception exists to this rule: performers must march backwards while
 traversed at 90° when immediately preceded by a forwards march with the
 same facing angle (Rock and Roll).
 Since it is impractical to one-eighty on one beat while maintaining a traversal
, a backwards march is needed until the facing direction changes.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To rotate the body to the desired facing direction, the hips should rotate
 half way to the desired angle, then the upper torso should rotate another
 half, resulting in the shoulders above having a net rotation of the desired
 facing rotation.
 For example, if you needed to traverse 90°, your hips will rotate 45°,
 and the upper body will rotate another 45°, resulting in a 90° rotation
 of the upper body.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Some instructors will suggest the thirds rule: divide the angle into thirds
 and apply each third to your knees, hips, and shoulders, effectively turning
 the entire upper body by the full angle.
 I disagree with this method since it often tends to intensify and increase
 error.
 By offsetting the knees, this induces non-ideal kinematics and effectively
 curves the actual marching path away from the target.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To healthily rotate the upper body, imagine pushing the shoulder behind
 forwards, instead of pulling the forwards shoulder back.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Is this right? Or do I have this backwards?
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It is also important to retain a proper posture and provide lower back
 support to reduce strain and soreness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Beginners will experience that they will 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

drift
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or march oblique to their intended marching path if they are Traversing.
 It is simple as just practicing to overcome this habit and remain on track.
 Extra attention must be given to the feet to achieve this.
 It may be helpful to overcompensate when first learning Traversing to effective
ly maintain the correct path.
