\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A left Diagonal Box 8 takes 8 steps towards the position 8 8:5 steps to
 the left and 8 8:5 forwards.
 Because of this, Diagonal Boxes will never have an integer ratio step size;
 it will be a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Except when you scale the distance by a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}.$
\end_inset

 But this is 
\emph on
never
\emph default
 done.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Pythagorean theorem states that, given a right triangle with legs 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, and hypotenuse
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{2}+B^{2}=C^{2}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Loomis1968"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Because of this, it is possible to calculate the actual step size.
 In this example, 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 represents the length of the march in steps, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 represent orthogonal imaginary legs composing this triangle.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
A^{2}+B^{2} & =C^{2}\\
8^{2}+8^{2} & =C^{2}\\
\sqrt{128}=8\sqrt{2} & =C
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, a left Diagonal Box 8 has a hypotenuse length of 
\begin_inset Formula $8\sqrt{2}\approx11.314\text{ steps}=\frac{8\sqrt{2}*22.5\text{in}}{36}=5\sqrt{2}\text{ yards}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is also easily calculable when assuming the diagonal of a square with
 side length 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

, also proven by the Pythagorean theorem.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

