 circumference, the member that follows that path must march proportionately
 further.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To further prove this, we know that the radius of the quarter circle is
 larger on the outside of the turn.
 The equation relating circumference to radius is 
\begin_inset Formula $C=2\pi r$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 increases, 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 increases.
 Hence, the march distance is larger on the outside of the turn.
\end_layout

