\begin_layout Subsubsection
Boom-crash
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the arrangement of the Star Spangled Banner played by our band, there
 exist 
\noun on
Boom-Crashes
\noun default
 that are heard throughout the song.
 Drum Majors conduct these sounds in the song specially.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The boom-crash consists of two parts: the 
\noun on
Boom
\noun default
 and the 
\noun on
Crash
\noun default
.
 They both correlate to two different moves done to indicate them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Boom-crashes are conducted on beats 1 and 2: boom on beat 1 and crash on
 beat 2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Boom
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The boom is a quick and firm—but not intense—punch to the conductor's chest
 with the right hand.
 On beat 1, instead of conducting the downbeat, the right hand makes a fist
 and is placed on the chest.
 This punch shouldn't knock back the conductor, but is firm and not floppy.
 The fingers of the fist will rest on the upper chest, knuckles pointing
 up and left.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Crash
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

booming,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the right hand is quickly released and the hand is opened, extending outwards
 and upwards, on beat 2.
 The palm shall be face up at its final position.
 Immediately after the crash, the right hand is brought back to the third-beat
 position.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Trumpet cue
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\noun on
Trumpet Cue 
\noun default
cues the trumpet fanfare in the B section of the Banner.
 This cue is simple and easy to perform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On beat 1, place the right hand outwards, palm up, fingers together, and
 hold this for two beats.
 On beat 3, bring the right hand back to the third-beat position.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Fermata
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\noun on
Fermata
\noun default
 is used to hold the band on one note for an extended period of time.
 There are two parts to a fermata, the 
\noun on
Hold
\noun default
 and the 
\noun on
Cinch
\noun default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Hold
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To hold the fermata, place one or more the hands near the ictus with the
 palm up.
 Use one hand (usually the dominant) on the first fermata and use both hands
 for the last fermata.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Cinch
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To cinch, take the extended hand (or both)—with the palm up from the hold—and
 invert it by making a counterclockwise circle with the hand.
 Once the hand is inverted (the palm is now facing down), 
