\begin_layout Subsubsection
Giving Feedback: The Feedback Sandwich
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Feedback ! Feedback sandwich
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pointing out what others are doing well is helpful, but does not address
 what needs to be improved.
 Using the 
\noun on
Feedback Sandwich
\noun default
 can allow you to provide both types of feedback while boosting the learner's
 confidence 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dohrenwend2002,docheff1990feedback,schartel2012giving"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The efficacy of the feedback sandwich is disputed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "doi:10.1080/01608061.2015.1093057,VonBergen2014,Cohn2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, but through personal experience I found it to be beneficial.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VonBergen2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provides some good guidelines for correct correcting, but these procedures
 are best suited for a more professional workplace environment where staff
 have time to prepare what they are going to say.
 But when you're on the field, you need to serve up that sandwich fast and
 get the feedback to them as soon as possible so they can learn most efficiently
 (you're not going to create a meeting and schedule conferences with each
 member and explain to them their feedback that way).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The concept is simple:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Give feedback on something good they are doing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Give feedback on something they could improve on
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Reinforce first good thing, or note something else they are doing good
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here are a couple of examples of good feedback sandwiches:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\emph on
Hey, great foot angle while marking time! Just make sure you're keeping
 your upper body motionless while you do it.
 Your mark time is getting better, keep it up!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\emph on
Great job on the backwards march; your heels never touched the ground! I
 see you're undershooting the yard line; try taking bigger steps—bigger
 than you might think you need.
 Great job keeping your upper body stable as well.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are some other factors to think about before you give feedback:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Is it the appropriate time and place? Give feedback immediately if you notice
 a wrong behavior in a fundamental (e.g., stepping off on the right foot)
 and delay lengthier feedback and provide it when it is appropriate to do
 so.
 Do you give the feedback in public or in private? Think about the situation
 and determine when it is appropriate (it's not a good idea to tell someone
 they are misbehaving in the middle of a set, unless you deem it is emergent).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Before you begin giving feedback, organize your thoughts so you have a clear
 message.
 A clear, precise set of feedback goes much further than 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

yeah, looks good but you could fix a couple things...
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Emphasize the positive without being patronizing.
 This is important but also tricky to do.
 The best way I found to do this is to be casual as you provide the feedback
 (i.e., don't sound like you're reading off of a script).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Follow up later to see how things have changed.
\end_layout

