\begin_layout Subsection
Pitch, Support & Volume
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:delivering-parameters"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, when delivering commands, we must always be thinking about what is
 going maximize the effective travel distance of our delivery.
 The standard pitch at which you yell can affect this.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is common for those with a deep voice (typically males) to raise their
 neutral speaking pitch to achieve this.
 The LO level of delivering may then rest around the common speaking pitch.
 Likewise, those with a higher voice (typically females) lower their voice.
 The HI level may then rest around common speaking pitch.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When delivering commands, it's also important to maximize your volume, while
 also not damaging your vocal cords.
 An effective Drum Major shout relies more on diction and pitch more than
 volume, although still necessary.
 Commands will travel long distances when supported with enough air.
 Just like playing a wind instrument—building air pressure before playing—it
 is necessary to build pressure to ensure a well supported delivery with
 the diaphragm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lindsay1970"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's also important to know what you are going to say before you say it.
 This seems obvious, but is obvious when not considered.
 Cutting yourself off halfway through a delivery may not only confuse the
 band, but can also show that you're not confident in what you're going
 to say.
 If you accidentally start delivering the wrong command, commit to it and
 fix the error after you are finished.
 The band may not even realized you delivered the wrong command.
 If you commenced a drill (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

HUP HUP RIGHT NOW!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), you can emergency stop it by blowing a long whistle tone.
 Instruct the band to revert to the initial position.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also know when it is appropriate to shout for delivery.
 If you are on the box (speaking into the microphone), you don't need to
 shout at full velocity.
 I recommend just loud-talking this to distinguish from normal banter, but
 not so loud you're damaging equipment or eardrums.
 See Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
