\begin_layout Section
Studying
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When you're a Drum Major, it is probably a good idea to know what you are
 going to teach the band.
 Therefore, it's an important idea to study necessary information before
 band camp.
 There are three main things you should analyze and familiarize yourself
 with before attempting to instruct the ensemble: the charts, the scores,
 and the fundamentals.
 Having a firm understanding of these three facets will help you throughout
 the week and continuing into the school year.
 I've talked previously about teaching fundamentals and the prep work needed
 in order to properly teach this to the band (see Subsection
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "subsec:formula for effective teaching"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), so I will focus on the charts and scores for this section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Charts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Studying the charts will help you become more familiar with how the band
 should appear on the field and how the show is structured.
 For example, if a member comes up to you not knowing where they should
 be in a certain set, having a firm understanding—of not just how to read
 the chart, but the details and forms of 
\emph on
this
\emph default
 year's chart—will help you help them out quicker and get them on their
 dot.
 Lots of freshmen have a hard time understanding how to read their dotsheet
 (see Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "sec:Interpreting-Your-Dotsheet"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for specifics on this), so knowing the chart to confirm their position
 is handy.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
During my freshman year, I was on the wrong side of the field for probably
 30 minutes when we first started dotting the first set until I realized
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

left
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 meant 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

left.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The lesson to learn is this: don't assume freshmen know what they are doing;
 you don't want to make them feel lost—but have confidence in their ability
 to learn!
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, having the charts memorized will help you during rehearsal.
 Much of the time spent at band camp—when not practicing fundamentals, rehearsin
g music, or eating bagels and popsicles—is spent drilling the sets of the
 show, constantly going back and forth between sets.
 Knowing the measures and counts of each set—as well as what the band looks
 like in each set—can help speed up rehearsal, especially when Mr.
 Larsen says, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

go back to set 12,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and everyone goes, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

which measure?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 You studied the charts, you know which measure it is!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Scores
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Besides the visual appearance of the band on the field, the next most important
 feature of a marching band is the music.
 To have great music, everyone must know and be able to play their part
 well.
 So, what part do Drum Majors learn? Everyone's part! Knowing the scores
 will help you on the field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having a strong command of the scores will indicate to you which parts and
 sections deserve the most attention and when.
 For example, during 2019's 
\emph on
Planes, Trains, and Automobiles
\emph default
, different songs required different conducting and cues depending on the
 song.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Low Rider
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 had heavy a trombone section, so it was important to cue trombones and
 conduct more specifically (since the trombones had the lead, or melody).
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Crazy Train
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 had special cues for tenor drums.
 The tenors played really interesting fills during some phrases in the song
 so it was important to emphasize it and cue it every time.
 Learning the scores goes hand-in-hand with learning the charts: knowing
 the measure numbers for sections in the song will be beneficial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
How to study the scores
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An approach can be applied to analyzing and studying scores 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Koval2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Mark time signatures, tempos, dynamics, modulations, fermatas, etc.
 with a highlighter.
 Use different colors for each.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Listen to recordings of the pieces and highlight the melody or focal element
 (which can change instrument, so do this bar by bar).
 Use a new color.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Highlight areas to conduct differently or specially, including cues, crescendos,
 decrescendos, fermatas, etc.
 Use a new color.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Translate your notations and markings into conducting styles.
 Use Laban elements and efforts to sculpt how you'll conduct each section.
 In the score, write down specifically how you'll execute this (exact efforts).
\end_layout

